  "text": "Envoy's gRPC health check protocol compliance is implemented in the `source/extensions/health_checkers/grpc/` directory with two primary source files: `health_checker_impl.h` and `health_checker_impl.cc`.\n\n## Primary Implementation\n\nThe **GrpcHealthCheckerFactory** class in `health_checker_impl.h` implements the `CustomHealthCheckerFactory` interface and is registered with the name \"envoy.health_checkers.grpc\". The factory's `createCustomHealthChecker()` method is called by the `HealthCheckerFactory::create()` method in `source/common/upstream/health_checker_impl.cc` when a gRPC health check configuration is detected (via the `kGrpcHealthCheck` case in the health check type switch statement).\n\nThe **GrpcHealthCheckerImpl** class extends `HealthCheckerImplBase` and manages the overall gRPC health checking behavior. It contains a nested **GrpcActiveHealthCheckSession** class that implements the actual protocol interaction:\n\n### HealthCheckRequest Handling\nThe `onInterval()` method in `GrpcActiveHealthCheckSession` sends a `grpc::health::v1::HealthCheckRequest` to the target service. It:\n1. Creates an HTTP/2 connection using `parent_.createCodecClient()`\n2. Prepares gRPC request headers for the `grpc.health.v1.Health/Check` method\n3. Serializes and sends the HealthCheckRequest message with optional service name parameter\n\n### HealthCheckResponse Parsing\nThe response handling is distributed across three methods:\n- **decodeData()**: Deserializes the gRPC frame containing `grpc::health::v1::HealthCheckResponse` using protobuf parsing\n- **decodeHeaders()**: Validates the HTTP/2 response status and gRPC metadata\n- **decodeTrailers()**: Extracts the gRPC status code from response trailers\n\n### Health Status Mapping\nThe **isHealthCheckSucceeded()** method evaluates the response:\n- Requires gRPC status code to be `Ok` (0)\n- Checks that `HealthCheckResponse.status()` equals `SERVING` (1)\n- Returns false for any other status including `NOT_SERVING` (2), `UNKNOWN` (0), and `SERVICE_UNKNOWN` (3)\n\nThe **logHealthCheckStatus()** method maps response statuses to human-readable labels:\n- `SERVING` → \"serving\" (healthy)\n- `NOT_SERVING` → \"not_serving\" (unhealthy)\n- `UNKNOWN` → \"unknown\" (treated as unhealthy)\n- `SERVICE_UNKNOWN` → \"service_unknown\" (unhealthy)\n- RPC errors → \"rpc_error\"\n\n## Configuration Schema\nThe gRPC health check configuration is defined in `api/envoy/config/core/v3/health_check.proto` with the `GrpcHealthCheck` message type that supports:\n- `service_name`: Optional parameter sent in HealthCheckRequest\n- `authority`: Overrides the default :authority header value\n- `initial_metadata`: Custom key-value pairs added to gRPC request headers\n\n## Supporting Infrastructure\nThe implementation relies on:\n- **source/common/upstream/health_checker_impl.h/cc**: Factory pattern registration and health check routing logic\n- **source/extensions/health_checkers/common/health_checker_base_impl.h/cc**: Base class providing timing, callbacks, and host status management\n- **src/proto/grpc/health/v1/health.pb.h**: Protocol buffer definitions for the standard gRPC health check service messages\n\nThe factory is registered via `REGISTER_FACTORY(GrpcHealthCheckerFactory, Server::Configuration::CustomHealthCheckerFactory)` in health_checker_impl.cc, making it available for automatic instantiation when a cluster's health check configuration includes the gRPC health check type."
